PRODUCTION
  Simulate next-update production for your sectors.

SYNTAX
  production [<sector-spec>]
  prod [<sector-spec>]

DESCRIPTION
  Shows what each of your sectors will produce at the next update,
  based on current efficiency, avail, materials on hand, and your
  tech/education level.  Nothing is changed — this is read-only.

  The simulation applies the same pre-production steps the update
  uses: food consumption (which affects civilian count), and
  efficiency building (which can change avail and effic).  Sectors
  below 60% efficiency after these steps are skipped.

OUTPUT COLUMNS
  sect   — sector coordinates
  des    — sector type mnemonic
  eff    — physical production efficiency (sector effic x resource quality)
  avail  — available work units
  make   — projected output (number + commodity mnemonic, or decimal for tech/res)
  p.e.   — tech-adjusted production efficiency
  cost   — dollar cost of this production run
  use1-3 — commodities consumed at projected output level
  max1-3 — commodities that would be consumed if inputs were unlimited
  max    — maximum possible output if inputs were unlimited

HOW LEVEL OUTPUT MAPS TO 'NATION' NUMBERS
  Sectors like libraries (l), parks (p), tech centers (t), and
  research labs (r) show a decimal "make" value with a '.' suffix
  instead of a commodity mnemonic.  This raw output becomes the
  number in your 'nation' report as follows:

  TECHNOLOGY and RESEARCH (from 't' and 'r' sectors):
    These accumulate directly each update.  The "make" value is
    added to your current level (before logarithmic slowdown above
    tech=1.0 and before decay at ~1%/update).
    Example: three tech centers each producing 0.7 tech/update
    will raise your tech level by ~2.1 per update net of decay.

  EDUCATION (from 'l' library sectors):
    Education is a moving average (window ~192 ETU at default).
    Raw edu output is scaled by:
      edu_rate = raw_output * 600000 / (total_civs * etu)
    Then averaged in:
      new_edu = (old_edu * 192 + edu_rate * etu) / (192 + etu)

    With 5000 civs and 96-ETU updates, a single 100% library
    producing ~25 raw edu/update pushes education up ~10 points
    on the first update from zero.  Education rises quickly at
    first, then slows as it approaches a plateau.

  HAPPINESS (from 'p' park sectors):
    Happiness works the same way but with a faster window (~48 ETU)
    and an additional factor (hap_edu) that decreases as education
    rises.  Educated populations need more parks to stay happy.
      hap_rate = raw_output * hap_edu * 600000 / (civs * etu)
      new_hap  = (old_hap * 48 + hap_rate * etu) / (48 + etu)
    See 'info happiness' for hap_edu values by education level.

  PRODUCTION EFFICIENCY (p.e.) FOR LEVEL SECTORS:
    Libraries and parks always produce at p.e.=1.0 (no requirement).
    Tech centers and research labs need education >= 5:
      p.e. = (education - 5) / (education + 5)
      edu=10: 33%  edu=20: 60%  edu=30: 71%  edu=50: 82%
    If p.e. is 0, your education is below 5 — build more libraries.

DIAGNOSTICS
  If "make" is much lower than "max", you are input-limited: the
  sector doesn't have enough raw materials.  Supply the missing
  commodity (shown in use1-3 vs max1-3) to reach full output.

  If p.e. is low or zero, your tech or education level is below the
  minimum required for that product type.  Use 'show product' to
  see requirements for each product.

  If make and max are both zero, check avail and effic — the sector
  may not have enough workers or may be below 60% efficiency.

EXAMPLE
  prod *            simulate production for all your sectors
  prod #2           sectors in realm 2
  prod ?des=i       all iron mines
  prod ?des=t       tech centers — check p.e. vs. education

